In order to understand the effects of solar-wind turbulence on the multi-scale evolution of the plasma, we must determine the nature of the fluctuations. Iroshnikov (1963) and Kraichnan (1965) suggest that MHD turbulence in a strongly magnetized medium is a manifestation of nonlinear collisions between counter-propagating AlfvÃ©n-wave packets. According to their statistically isotropic theory, the AlfvÃ©n-wave-collision mechanism leads to a power law of the magnetic-field spectrum with183E(k)â¼k-3/2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} E(k)\sim k^{-3/2} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}in the inertial range. This work introduced the framework of wave turbulence (see also Howes etÂ al. 2014a) into plasma-turbulence research. Wave turbulence accounts for the fact that a plasma, unlike a neutral fluid, carries plasma waves as linear normal modes for the system (see Sect.Â 4.1). The linear response of the system still plays a role in the dynamics of the turbulence, even though the evolution of the turbulence is nonlinear. Therefore, fluctuations in wave turbulence retain certain characteristics of the plasmaâs linear normal modes such as propagation and polarization properties. In the wave-turbulence framework, the identification of the nature of plasma turbulence is thus informed by the identification of the dominant wave modes of the turbulence. As a caveat to this picture, we note that nonlinear interactions may generate fluctuations that are not (linear) normal modes of the system as those described in Sect.Â 4.3. These driven modes may behave unexpectedly, and linear theory does not predict their properties.

