				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf{j}$$\end{document}, which are a type of coherent structure as introduced in Sect.Â 5.4.1 (Karimabadi etÂ al. 2013; TenBarge and Howes 2013; Howes 2016). Current sheets are candidate regions for magnetic reconnection, which demonstrates the direct link between turbulence and reconnection (Matthaeus etÂ al. 1984; Servidio etÂ al. 2009, 2010; Osman etÂ al. 2014b), and reconnection acts as a dissipation channel for the turbulent fluctuations (RetinÃ² etÂ al. 2007; Sundkvist etÂ al. 2007; Cerri and Califano 2017; Shay etÂ al. 2018). On the other hand, reconnection sites are inherently unstable to the tearing instability, which progressively fragments them into smaller and smaller current sheets (Loureiro etÂ al. 2007; Lapenta 2008; Loureiro and Uzdensky 2016; Tenerani etÂ al. 2016). In this way, reconnection sites generate a cascade to smaller scales by themselves and thus drive turbulence. In these progressively fragmented current sheets, the reconnection time gradually becomes faster than any other timescale, including the nonlinear time (Pucci and Velli 2014). When this condition is established, reconnection is able to interrupt the cascade of AlfvÃ©n-wave turbulence (Boldyrev and Loureiro 2017; Loureiro and Boldyrev 2017; Mallet etÂ al. 2017). Therefore, reconnection must be considered when studying turbulence dynamics at small scales.

